node.text:
The Arctic National Wildlife Refuge is home to more than 200 species of birds and is sacred land for the Gwich'in people—but it has never been in greater danger. On the Arctic Refuge Day of Action, learn more about this vast Alaskan wilderness and what you can do to help protect this critical habitat.

Join us in taking action to #ProtectTheArctic today: https://www.audubon.org/arcticrefuge

node.title: Why Birds Need the Arctic Refuge

node.text:
Did you know that the Boreal Forest is home to between 1-3 billion birds that nest in the region each year? Not only that: it’s a nature based climate solution, holding about 12% of land-based carbon reserves. Audubon is working closely with our chapters, members, and Indigenous partners to protect one of the largest intact forests left on planet Earth. 🌲

On #WorldMigratoryBirdDay, learn more about conservation efforts for North America’s bird nursery: audubon.org/borealforests

node.title: The Boreal Forest: A Bird Haven

node.text:
Did you know that the Great Lakes provide drinking water to 40 million people and its coastal habitats support more than 350 bird species? As climate change, coastal development, and invasive species threaten these communities and habitats, @audubongreatlakes is ready with a bold plan.

Our new report, Restoring the Great Lakes for Birds and People, uses science to pinpoint the highest-priority coastal regions for birds, water quality, and coastal resiliency—focusing conservation where it’s needed most. Learn more and join us on this journey: https://bit.ly/397ppSG

node.title: Protecting Birds in the Great Lakes

The fierce and resilient Bald Eagle is a common sight today, but did you know the species was on the brink of extinction in the 1970s? Eagles recovered thanks to increased protections under the Endangered Species Act, but new rules would weaken it. 

Urge your members of Congress today to stand up for this critical law: https://bit.ly/3tjk9TH

Then, tell Congress to take action to support cheatgrass control and sagebrush habitat restoration: http://audubon.org/cheatgrass

node.text: Audubon’s Seabird Institute works to restore Atlantic Puffin and other seabird populations to islands off the coast of Maine. Visit https://www.audubon.org/seabirdsummer

node.text:
If the bird world had a pageant and the theme was feather boas, this Kori Bustard would be a winner! 🪶💃⁠
⁠
While leading a photographic safari of Kenya in October, Aaron Baggenstos (@aaronbaggenstos) was fortunate enough to catch a male Kori Bustard in the midst of his impressive courtship display. The world’s heaviest flying bird, standing erect in a field of tall brown grass, put on a show for the visitors.⁠
⁠
He stuck his large black-and-white feathers out underneath his tail and held his head back with cheeks bulging, his crest upright and bill open. He inflated his gular pouch, forming a white throat "balloon." He enhanced his performance with an exaggerated bouncing and emitted a low-pitched booming noise with his neck at maximum inflation, snapping his bill open and shut. Seeing this extraordinary display was an experience Aaron will never forget.⁠
⁠
Aaron’s flamboyant photograph made this year’s #AudubonPhotographyAwards top 100 list.

node.text:
Have you seen any unfamiliar birds in your area lately? Maybe you checked your calendar and worried that summer is flying by far too fast—but fall has already begun for many bird species. While mid-August to mid-October is peak fall migration season, some other species started their expeditions as early as June.⁠
⁠
Take, for instance, the Bullock’s Oriole, a species that undergoes molt migration each year. In order to molt more easily and with better resources before finishing its journey, it migrates to the monsoon-rich region between the desert Southwest and northern Mexico. By early August, the seasonally predictable rains create a “second spring” that cools the area’s temperature and restores vegetation—giving the songbird plenty of resources to power through the molt and complete its migration. ⁠
⁠
What other species might you be able to find as fall migration ramps up? Tap the link in our bio to find out—and learn the science behind these marvelous cycles.⁠
⁠
A Bullock's Oriole perched on a pine branch. 📷: Rick Derevan (@rickderevan)/Audubon Photography Awards

node.text:
You don’t mess with a Carib Grackle’s cactus fruit meal. 🌵⁠
⁠
Lawrence Worcester captured this feisty bird snacking on some cactus fruit in Simplicity Bay. During the short fruiting season, competition can lead to territorial disputes and even injury. The spiny sharp needles of the cactus makes it tricky for birds to get the foothold needed to eat the sweet flesh of its fruit, increasing the tension and fighting that surrounds a fruiting patch. But this grackle had the treat all to itself—at least for a short while.⁠
⁠
The final shot shows the jet-black bird sitting atop a cactus fruit, facing the camera with bright yellow eyes and a wide-open bill revealing a mouthful of sticky pink flesh. The grackle’s wings are close to its sides, a few feathers ruffled at its shoulders. Its feet grasp the fuchsia fruit that sits along a green cactus stalk, sharp needles protruding from all sides.⁠
⁠
Lawrence’s entertaining photo was selected to be in this year’s #AudubonPhotographyAwards top 100 list.

node.text:
Some birds like the Common Cuckoo sneak their eggs into other birds’ nests in order to rear their young. This unconventional parenting method—known as brood parasitism—is vulnerable to environmental changes that affect host species. If the hosting bird arrives at nesting sites too early or starts nesting in a new location, there may be no place for the parasite to rehome its eggs and will fail to reproduce.⁠
⁠
As global warming ramps up, brood parasites are about to have their adaptability tested. Hosts are already moving to new areas or breeding sooner as climates warm and the parasitic birds may struggle to keep up. But scientists predict that as the climate changes, so will the behavior of brood parasites—they may seek out a wider variety of hosts or adapt to a warmer environment. Depending on the species, some brood parasites will adapt quite well, while others may struggle.⁠
⁠
Tap the link in our bio to read the full story on avian brood parasites and how climate change will test their adaptability. ☝️⁠
⁠
A Dunnock (left) feeding a juvenile Common Cuckoo. 📷: FLPA/Alamy

node.text:
May the rest of your day be as peaceful as this Atlantic Puffin at golden hour. ☀️💛⁠
⁠
Sunil Gopalan (@birdtog) photographed this bird on a remote island in the Shetlands where seabirds outnumber humans. The island’s usual rain cleared in the evening just as the sun set behind the cliffs, giving Sunil the perfect photograpy conditions. As he lay down on the ground and pointed his lens directly at the sun, he captured the puffin returning with two wildflowers in its beak to line its burrow. Walking amid pink thrift flowers that appear gold in the sunlight, the bird’s orange-and-black beak contrasts with its white belly and black shoulders and neck.⁠
⁠
Sunil’s heartwarming picture made this year’s #AudubonPhotographyAwards top 100 list.

node.text:
Why are #BirdFriendly buildings important? Up to 1 billion birds die each year from building collisions, making collisions with man-made structures a leading cause of bird deaths in the U.S. Recently, Illinois took an important step to help mitigate that by signing the Bird Safe Buildings Act—which requires bird-friendly design to be incorporated into the construction and renovation of state-owned buildings. ⁠
⁠
“By making simple adjustments to new Illinois state building projects, this new law will help mitigate the unnecessary deaths of countless numbers of migrating birds every year,” says Kristin Murphy, government affairs associate for @AudubonGreatLakes. ⁠
⁠
Tap the link in our bio to learn more about this important new law. ⁠
⁠
Black-and-white Warbler perched on a mossy outcropping. 📷: Jessica Nelson (@gagglephotog)/Audubon Photography Awards

node.text:
Would you want to get into a staring contest with this Virginia Rail? 👀⁠
⁠
In order to get an intimate perspective of this wader, Joshua Galicki (@galicki_photography) got  as low to the ground as he could. He incorporated some out-of-focus foreground elements to supplement—but not distract—from the bird's gaze. Obscured by blurred flowers, the Virginia Rail looks head-on at the camera. The diffused light provides some soft, pastel colors, and slim lines of white feathers outline the bird’s red eyes.⁠
⁠
Joshua’s captivating shot was selected to be in this year’s #AudubonPhotographyAwards top 100 list.

When @audubon_fl shorebird coordinator Kylie Wilson (@khelene94) came across Least Terns nesting on South Lido Beach in June—where they hadn’t previously been—she knew it was going to be a busy summer.⁠
⁠
From hurricanes to fireworks, banding chicks to moving colonies, Kylie sat down to talk more about her action-packed summer monitoring sea and shorebirds as a bird biologist for Audubon Florida. Given the breadth of her experience, she has plenty of wisdom on how beachgoers can leave a smaller footprint and #ShareTheShore with nesting birds. 🏖️⁠
⁠
To read the full interview with Kylie, tap the link in our bio.⁠
⁠

Those aren’t snowflakes flurrying around this White Ibis—they’re thousands of tiny flying insects. 🪰 South Carolina bird photographer Kelley Luikey (@naturemuseimagery) is used to being swarmed and stung, but this time, they became part of the scene while shooting one afternoon in early March.⁠
⁠
Kelley arrived at one of her favorite rookeries, set up her camera, and took a peek in the viewfinder to find thousands of bugs backlit and framed by the glowing red samaras of a maple tree. Within a few minutes, a White Ibis landed on a branch, and Kelley framed it with the tree in the foreground and the horde of bugs floating all around.⁠
⁠
Her completed shot shows the White Ibis in brilliant white breeding plumage standing on the maple tree branch, its bright red legs and bill matching the red leaves. The thousands of bugs, backlit by the late afternoon sun, fill the frame like tiny sprites.⁠
⁠
Kelley’s enchanting photograph made this year’s #AudubonPhotographyAwards top 100 list.

node.text:
⁠Social media is a boon for bird photographers. You’ve probably found that you can share your photos with a much larger audience and perhaps you can spark other people’s appreciation of birds with your work. But while there are plenty of best ethical practices to be aware of while photographing, there’s a whole other side of ethical considerations after you’ve taken your shot.⁠
⁠
For example, consider something as simple as deciding whether or not to post the location of your shot. Before publicly revealing the location of a bird—especially endangered or nesting birds—think about what kind of disturbance it could bring. A flood of visitors could wreak havoc on ecologically sensitive areas or disturb homeowners living nearby. As we build online birding communities, we owe it to the birds to ensure their protection comes first.⁠
⁠
On #WorldPhotographyDay, celebrate the craft of bird photography by learning how you can be a more responsible bird photographer in the digital age. Tap the link in our bio to find out how.⁠
⁠
A Great Gray Owl perched on a branch. 📷: Melissa Groo (@melissagroo)

node.text:
Be like this American Goldfinch and make sure you stop to admire the sunflowers every now and again. 🌻⁠
⁠
Jules Jacobs (@julesjacobs_photo) was admiring the sunflowers in the massive garden of the McKee-Beshers Wildlife Management Area, when he saw one of them unexpectedly start to move. This brilliant yellow American Goldfinch bounced from flower to flower, its feathers blending in seamlessly with the blooms, and its distinctive black cap and wings preventing it from being entirely camouflaged. This quiet moment in a sunflower field that’s usually crowded with tourists reminded Jules that with a soft footprint, humans can enjoy the beauty of places like this while preserving them for the birds that need them.⁠
⁠
Jules’s vibrant photo made this year’s #AudubonPhotographyAwards top 100 list.

#BirdsTellUs we need to act on climate now. This week the U.S. Bureau of Reclamation announced 2022 will bring unprecedented water shortages to Arizona, Nevada and the Republic of Mexico—threatening the communities and wildlife that rely on Colorado River water supply. ⁠
⁠
“Historically, water management was based on the premise that drought would be followed by wet years. Climate change means we can no longer make that assumption. Good short-term solutions may not be sustainable,” says Jennifer Pitt, Audubon’s Colorado River program director. ⁠
⁠
As new operating rules for the river are crafted, it’s vital we heed the water rights of Native American tribes, invest in long-term strategies promoting the basin’s resiliency, and ensure that decision-makers don’t raid the last drops of water supporting Colorado River habitats. ⁠
⁠
Tap the link in our bio to learn more about the impacts of these water shortages on the Southwest and what can be done to ensure the plans in place to mitigate it are designed for the 21st century. ⁠
⁠
A Willow Flycatcher sings while perched on a branch. 📷: Susan Ward/Audubon Photography Awards
